1.How to fetch only first and last line of a file using head a tail
we can do that by using the following command-
Syntax: head -1 <filename>; tail -1 <filename>
ex: below I wanted to print 1st and last line of file, so I used
head -1 alpha.txt; tail -1 alpha.txt[;= used to run both the commands sequentially]
 

2. What is the use of the below command-
   head file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt
This command is used to fetch the info of the first 10 lines written in each of the text file on the terminal.
ex: Below I used to show the contents/lines of each file on the terminal, so I used
Syntax: head bravo.txt charlie.txt delta.txt
 

3. How can you suppress file headers when using multiple files?
   hint: head -q file1.txt file2.txt
We can use the following command as given in hint we can use [-q-quiet] command 
Syntax: head -q <file1-name> <file2-name> <file3-name>, but there won’t be any gaps between the words in order to distinguish between them.
ex: head -q bravo.txt charlie.txt delta.txt
 





4. How do you print all lines except the last 10 lines of a file?
We can do that by using the following command-
Syntax: head -n -10 <filename>
ex: here in the below picture I have listed all the lines and wanted to print all except last 10 lines so I used 
head -n -10 file2.txt
 





